{'post_title': '', 'post_text': 'Paul, in that instance as a way to identify smart people it makes a lot of sense for it not to be invite only. <p>But it has triggered my thinking about how to create dense communities around diverse knowledge areas. So it would be cool to do this with scientific papers and get people to register with university email addresses to generate trust and preserve fidelity. I know digg and reddit are pretty mainstream but allowing people to create specific knowledge networks on this platform would be cool. Where its an industry group or networking organisation it would be a great way to pool knowledge and if need be preserve the value of the information by  requiring users to be trusted by at least one person.  ', 'hanesst_id': 484, 'post_type': 'comment', 'post_parent': 360, 'username': 'sharpshoot', 'pwd_hash': 'HbXwdcp6Yi', 'post_url': ''},
