{'post_title': '', 'post_text': 'The market has a natural tendency to segement. This trend is driven by both, the consumers and the businesses. Considering that point in mind, I believe that the next big social network/startup will be much smaller than MySpace. We are in the era of super-niches; the market we appeal to will get smaller as the competition among startups increase.<p>That said, I would like to propose one &#34;lesson&#34; I did not mention in the article: &#34;As the target niche becomes more narrow, so will the funding&#34;. A niche that is sufficiently small might not attract any funding at all! So there is a downside to being small that must remain in check if you wish to attract funding. Enjoy :)\n- Jawad Shuaib', 'hanesst_id': 810, 'post_type': 'comment', 'post_parent': 807, 'username': 'python_kiss', 'pwd_hash': 'MhJ5VBzoTs', 'post_url': ''},
{'post_title': 'Anatomy of a Successful Social Network', 'post_text': '', 'hanesst_id': 811, 'post_type': 'story', 'post_parent': -1, 'username': 'python_kiss', 'pwd_hash': 'MhJ5VBzoTs', 'post_url': 'http://m4th.com/Articles/Article.php?Article-Title=Anatomy-of-a-Successful-Social-Network'},
{'post_title': '', 'post_text': "The number one thing that many startups fail at is defining a business model. While 2007 holds great promises for startup buyouts, that alone should not be a startup's business model. For every startup that gets bought by Google, there are a hundred others that don't. Simply put, a business is not a business if it does not make money.\n- Jawad Shuaib", 'hanesst_id': 812, 'post_type': 'comment', 'post_parent': 811, 'username': 'python_kiss', 'pwd_hash': 'MhJ5VBzoTs', 'post_url': ''},
